Inert Gas Technology (IGT) shoots pellets using a pneumatic inert gas cylinder in place of conventional spring systems. Advantages of IGT include extreme durability; more accuracy and precision; and steady, consistent power. Without spring friction, the cocking effort is more constant and smooth. Combining Whisper technology with an integrated noise dampener ND52, this break-action air rifle delivers more velocity and terminal penetration, while producing less noise and vibration. All-weather tactical thumbhole stock. 4x32 Gamo scope included.

Caliber: 5.56x45mm NATO Chamber Barrel: 16" M4 Profile Barrel, WASP Treated 4140 Chrome-Moly Steel, 1:7" Twist Hand Guard: M4 Hand Guard Sights/Gas Block:"F" Marked Front Sight Base W.A.S.P. Treated Barrel (Weapon Armament Surface Protection) is a salt bath ferritic nitrocarburizing surface conversion process or more commonly referred to as nitriding. The nitriding conversion is applied to the barrel inside and out, along with the front sight base on our LE rifles and uppers. Nitriding offers improved wear, abrasion, and corrosion resistance when compared to hard chrome lining or phosphating. Unlike chrome lining, where the chrome is built up on the surface, nitriding converts the surface without the risk of dimensional build up. CMMG Pioneered the use of this nitriding process on AR barrels and has been using it for many years.

My Hamilton is the:  "Khaki King" model; Automatic Movement [SWISS] All Stainless Steel Case; and I went the extra mile & tracked down a "New Old Stock" Vintage Hamilton St. Steel Bracelet w/ the "Deployment" Clasp, to make this "all-original" and the "Best of the Best."
I can forward to you some add'l photographs, description details, etc.

This Hamilton is serial-numbered; The "Real McCoy," and I have the original seal, box/case & Owner's Manuel, etc.

 Living in these days/times, trying my best to look after  my Mom, etc. it keeps me awake nights knowing I'm not able to defend the property as well as I need to be. (And, used to be before I sold off most of my collection, left Maine  and moved south here to Tennessee.)

Perhaps some of my fellow "Enthusiasts"  here on the "TENNESSEE ARMSLIST" might know of any "Leads" I could look in to, etc.?  I'm really hoping to get our new home protected just as soon as possible.

I appreciate all you guys/gals here, too - a friend suggested I "Hook Up" w/ some of my fellow "Brother Gun Enthusiasts" here in & on the Tennessee Armslist to try to help me find some solutions.

Thank you for checking my "Post" out, & I'm grateful too, for even any "Suggestions," etc. that you might be willing to share with me to help me get set up, & situated here in the Deep South.

postcontent:
This is a LeFever Nitro Special. It has WESTERN FIELD DELUXE & MONTGOMERY WARDS & CO. stamped on the barrels. It has two of the three options available with the Western Field guns by special order: dual bead sights and a soft rubber butt pad. The only other option was the ejector that came later.
None of the Western Field guns frames were case hardened, this one was. There are traces of case hardening color under the front of the trigger guard, and on the top tang. The Western Field guns had a setter at point stamped into the frame sides. This one has the LeFever Nitro Special Duck in the Swamp scene. It has serial numbers matching on the frame, for end and barrels that are consistent with a LeFever Nitro Special made in 1929. The serial numbers are not in the Western Field range. The Western Field guns stocks were not checkered and were not normally good Walnut, the stocks on this gun are checkered and have a bit of tiger striping in the walnut.

It’s in an unadulterated form and in perfect functioning condition.

The bores are pristine. Both of the sighting beads have been broken. Bluing on the barrels is excellent with a very few minor surface scratches. The Duck in the Swamp scenes are light, but distinguishable. They aren't worn, just lightly stamped. The frame is dark, but there is no indication that it has been blued.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Finnish Mosin Nagant M39
postcontent:
I've added better photos. You can view them in higher resolution here: http://imgur.com/a/KYfFr

Price dropped 11/09/13.

100% blue, unissued condition w/ MINT bore and crown (yes, really) in 1967 dated plum heavy profile barrel. Receiver and bolt are captured Soviet, w/ 1936-dated hex receiver showing minor blued over pitting above the stock line - this part would have been salvaged from a dead man's 91/30 during the Winter War. Bolt is "Finn matched" to the barrel shank. NEW condition postwar stock with no cracks, dings or plugs, carefully shimmed by the Finns. Late date and no maker on barrel shank makes this a relatively rare example. Comes with a free Finnish leather sling, correct for late-date rifle. Chambered in 7.62x54r. Nice looking gun with an interesting provenance. This is arguably the best variation of the Mosin Nagant in service rifle configuration and certainly the most accurate.
